C[Ness: Thank you for reviewing my game.  I thought I played pretty well, but I still came up 13 points short.

I think that your biggest problem is that you are not very good at seeing the right direction of play.

What is "direction of play"? it is a general feeling for where you should be putting your stones. Where on the board the big moves are. What sort of result you should be aiming to get, rather than the details of the tactics you should use to get there (your tactics seem to be relatively good). So it is at the whole-board, instinct level of Go.

Although I say it is instinct, it is not something you automatically know, it is something you have to learn. Partly by thinking what is happening in your own games, but study can also help. Perhaps one of the best books about this is "Set Strong at the Opening". It is a lot of full-board opening problems, and for a lot of them, the way you get to the answer is to look at the board, spot the important direction of play, then that tells you where you need to put a stone. Even if GSATO does not use the word 'direction' much, that is what is going on in its explanations.

"Get Strong at Attacking" may have more examples of finding the right direction of play in the middle game, but I am less familiar with that book so am not completely sure. Also, "The Great Joseki Debates" talks about direction of play a lot.

You need to study direction of play until it has become instinctive for you.]
