But if you want an alternative, you could consider H3 (A). After you have played A, an invasion at B might be a good follow-up, since it splits white into two groups, neither of which are very strong.


That is another aspect of good direction of play. You want to play moves now that will give you the chance to play more good moves in the future. 

Notice that this is not quite the same a sente. A sente move is a move that the opponent must answer now, or he will suffer a big loss immediately. A move with a good follow-up is a good move now, and if the opponent does nothing now, you will be able to play another reasonably big move later. 

This is something you might notice if you look at professional games. They don't just play good moves. They always seem to be in a position where they have several good moves to choose from next. Now in my games, I sometimes get to a position where I can't think of a good move to play. There was something subtly wrong with my earlier moves. That just doesn't happen to pros.]
